  <slide>
    <title>History of Built-in Accessibility</title>
    <contents>
      <ul>
        <li>First introduced in the late 1980's as accessibility utilities, becomes standard part of MS-DOS, Windows and Apple OS</li>
        <li>Windows 95 maintains requirement for full keyboard support (1995)</li>
        <li>VoiceOver/Zoom integrated into OS X 10.4 (2011)</li>
      </ul>
    </contents>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Accessibility Features of Operating System</title>
    <contents>
      <h2>Laptops and Desktops</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="http://www.microsoft.com/enable/products/windows10/">Accessibility in Windows 10</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://www.apple.com/accessibility/osx/">OS X. Designed with your abilities in mind</a></li>
        <p><a href="https://wiki.gnome.org/Accessibility/">GNOME Desktop Accessibility Wiki</a></p>
      </ul>

      <h2>Tablets and Phones</h2>
      <ul>
        <p><a href="http://www.apple.com/accessibility/ios/">iOS. A wide range of features for a wide range of needs.</a></p>
        <li><a href="https://support.google.com/accessibility/android/">Android Accessibility Help Center</a></li>
      </ul>
    </contents>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Summary</title>
    <contents>
      <h2>Physical</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Sticky keys</li>
        <li>Mouse keys</li>
        <li>Repeat rate</li>
        <li>Keypress timing</li>
        <li>On screen keyboards for pointing devices (e.g. trackball, eye tracking)</li>
        <li>Voice commands</li>
      </ul>
      <h2>Visual</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>High contrast and other customizable themes</li>
        <li>Font size and family</li>
        <li>Mouse pointer sized and style</li>
        <li>Magnification</li>
        <li>Speech output</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>Hearing</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Caption preference</li>
        <li>Flash screen for system sounds</li>
      </ul>
    </contents>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Sticky Keys</title>
    <contents>
      <ul>
        <li>Allows one finger typing, by temporarily locking down modifier keys.</li>
        <li>Press shift key five times to turn on or off.</li>
      </ul>
    </contents>
  </slide>

